\section{Introduction}

The Dualatalis calculus provides a universal substrate for symbolic
dynamics, rewriting systems, and structural evolution. Independently,
the kernel provides a physically meaningful generative mechanism for
the formation of filaments, spirals, networks, and coherent structures
across scales. When combined, these two frameworks yield a unified
theory of structure: Dualatalis supplies the categorical and topological
infrastructure, while the kernel supplies the dynamical engine.

This document formalizes the integration of these two systems. The
kernel is discretized into a canonical rewrite operator, which becomes
the evolution operator $\varphi$ of Dualatalis. Universe configurations
become words, local field states become symbols, and kernel dynamics
become rewrite rules. The resulting system is capable of expressing
cosmological, biological, computational, and mathematical structure
formation within a single formalism.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Kernel Formalization}

\subsection{Continuous Kernel}

Let $u(x,t)$ denote the local state of the system, consisting of fields
such as density, phase, velocity, or geometric data. The kernel is a
differential operator of the form:


\[
  \partial_t u = \mathcal{K}[u],
\]


where $\mathcal{K}$ includes gradient terms, rotational terms, coupling
kernels, and nonlinear interactions.

\subsection{Discretization}

Discretize space into sites indexed by $i$, and time into steps of size
$\Delta t$. Let $u_i^t$ denote the state at site $i$ and time $t$.
Define the discrete update:


\[
  u_i^{t+1/2} = u_i^t + \Delta t \, \mathcal{K}[u^t]_i.
\]



\subsection{Growth and Repair Decomposition}

Define:


\[
  r_{\mathrm{g}} : \Sigma \to \Sigma^{*}
\]


as the growth rule corresponding to the forward kernel update, and


\[
  r_{\mathrm{r}} : \Sigma \to \Sigma^{*}
\]


as the repair rule enforcing invariants such as normalization,
conservation, or geometric constraints.

\subsection{Canonical $\varphi$-Operator}

The kernel induces the Dualatalis evolution operator:


\[
  \varphi(w) =
  \begin{cases}
    r_{\mathrm{r}}(r_{\mathrm{g}}(w)), & r_{\mathrm{r}} \text{ exists},\\
    r_{\mathrm{g}}(w), & \text{otherwise}.
  \end{cases}
\]



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Dualitas Embedding}

\subsection{Alphabet}

Let $\Sigma$ be the set of all possible local field states at a site.

\subsection{Words as Universe Configurations}

A configuration of the discretized universe is a word:


\[
  w = s_{i_1} s_{i_2} \dots s_{i_n} \in \Sigma^{*}.
\]



\subsection{Kernel Evolution as Rewrite Dynamics}

The kernel update corresponds exactly to:


\[
  w_{t+1} = \varphi(w_t).
\]



\subsection{Universe Histories}

The orbit:


\[
  \mathcal{O}(w_0) = \{ w_t : t \ge 0 \}
\]


is the history of a universe generated by the kernel.
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Attractors of the Kernel}

\subsection{Fixed Universes}

A configuration $w^{*}$ is a fixed universe if:


\[
  \varphi(w^{*}) = w^{*}.
\]


These correspond to static equilibria of the kernel: stationary
structures, frozen geometries, or steady-state field configurations.

\subsection{Cyclic Universes}

A universe is periodic of period $p \ge 2$ if:


\[
  \varphi^{p}(w) = w.
\]


These correspond to oscillatory or rotating structures generated by the
kernel.

\subsection{Quasiperiodic Universes}

If the Koopman spectrum of $\varphi$ lies on the unit circle and the
entropy vanishes:


\[
  \rho(U_{\varphi}) = 1, \qquad h(\varphi) = 0,
\]


the universe exhibits quasiperiodic evolution.

\subsection{Chaotic Universes}

If the entropy is positive:


\[
  h(\varphi) > 0,
\]


the kernel generates chaotic universes with sensitive dependence on
initial conditions.

\subsection{Universal Universes}

A universe is universal if the kernel simulates a universal Turing
machine. Formally:


\[
  \exists E : \mathcal{C} \to \Sigma^{*}
  \quad \text{s.t.} \quad
  E(\mathrm{Next}(c)) = \varphi(E(c)).
\]


Such universes can encode arbitrary computation and exhibit maximal
structural richness.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Renormalization Group Flow}

\subsection{Parameter Space}

Let $\theta$ denote the set of kernel parameters (coupling strengths,
diffusion constants, rotational terms, etc.). Each $\theta$ defines a
distinct evolution operator:


\[
  \varphi_{\theta}.
\]



\subsection{RG Transformation}

Define the renormalization transformation:


\[
  \mathcal{R} : \theta \mapsto \theta',
\]


corresponding to coarse-graining the universe and rescaling the kernel.

\subsection{Fixed Points}

A fixed point satisfies:


\[
  \mathcal{R}(\theta^{*}) = \theta^{*}.
\]


The corresponding $\varphi_{\theta^{*}}$ generates a scale-invariant
universe.

\subsection{Basins of Attraction}

The basin of a fixed point is:


\[
  \mathcal{B}(\theta^{*})
  = \{ \theta : \lim_{n \to \infty} \mathcal{R}^{n}(\theta) = \theta^{*} \}.
\]



\subsection{Universes as RG Attractors}

Each RG fixed point corresponds to a class of universes with identical
large-scale structure. Thus the RG flow classifies universes generated
by the kernel.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Subshift Structure of the Kernel}

\subsection{Allowed Patterns}

The language of the kernel is:


\[
  \mathcal{L}(\varphi)
  = \{ u \in \Sigma^{*} : u \text{ appears in some } w_t \}.
\]



\subsection{Forbidden Patterns}

Forbidden patterns are:


\[
  \mathcal{F}(\varphi) = \Sigma^{*} \setminus \mathcal{L}(\varphi).
\]



\subsection{Subshift of Admissible Universes}

Define the subshift:


\[
  X_{\varphi}
  = \{ x \in \Sigma^{\mathbb{N}} :
       \text{all finite blocks of } x \in \mathcal{L}(\varphi) \}.
\]



\subsection{SFT Universes}

If $\mathcal{F}(\varphi)$ is finite, the universe space is a shift of
finite type (SFT).

\subsection{Sofic Universes}

If $\mathcal{F}(\varphi)$ is regular, the universe space is sofic.

\subsection{Entropy of the Kernel}

The structural entropy is:


\[
  h(\varphi)
  = \lim_{n \to \infty}
    \frac{1}{n} \log |\mathcal{L}_n(\varphi)|.
\]


This measures the growth rate of admissible local structures.
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Spectral Theory of the Kernel}

\subsection{Observables on Universes}

Let $\mathcal{X} = \Sigma^{*}$ denote the space of discrete universe
configurations. An observable is any function:


\[
  f : \mathcal{X} \to \mathbb{C}.
\]


Examples include:


\[
  f(w) = |w|, \qquad
  f_a(w) = \#\{ i : w_i = a \}, \qquad
  f_u(w) = \mathbf{1}_{u \subseteq w}.
\]



\subsection{Koopman Operator}

The kernel induces a linear operator on observables:


\[
  (U_{\varphi} f)(w) = f(\varphi(w)).
\]


Even though $\varphi$ is nonlinear, $U_{\varphi}$ is linear.

\subsection{Eigenfunctions and Modes}

An eigenfunction satisfies:


\[
  U_{\varphi} f = \lambda f.
\]


The eigenvalue $\lambda$ determines the growth or decay of the mode.

\subsection{Spectral Decomposition}

If $U_{\varphi}$ admits a spectral resolution:


\[
  f = \sum_k c_k \psi_k,
\]


then:


\[
  f(\varphi^{t}(w))
  = \sum_k c_k \lambda_k^{t} \psi_k(w).
\]


Thus the kernel’s evolution decomposes into spectral modes.

\subsection{Spectral Radius}

Define:


\[
  \rho = \max_k |\lambda_k|.
\]


Classification:


\[
  \rho < 1 \Rightarrow \text{decay}, \qquad
  \rho = 1 \Rightarrow \text{neutral}, \qquad
  \rho > 1 \Rightarrow \text{growth}.
\]



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Homotopy of Universe Histories}

\subsection{Rewrite Graph of the Kernel}

Define the rewrite graph:


\[
  G_{\varphi} = (V, E),
\]


where:


\[
  V = \Sigma^{*}, \qquad
  E = \{ (w, \varphi(w)) \}.
\]


Each vertex is a universe configuration; each edge is a kernel update.

\subsection{Paths and Homotopy}

A path is a sequence:


\[
  w_0 \to w_1 \to \dots \to w_n.
\]


Homotopy identifies paths that differ only by associativity of rewrite
composition:


\[
  (w \to \varphi(w)) \circ (\varphi(w) \to \varphi^{2}(w))
  \simeq
  (w \to \varphi^{2}(w)).
\]



\subsection{Fundamental Groupoid}

The fundamental groupoid:


\[
  \Pi_{1}(G_{\varphi})
\]


classifies homotopy classes of universe histories.

\subsection{Loops and Periodic Universes}

A loop corresponds to a periodic universe:


\[
  w \to \varphi(w) \to \dots \to \varphi^{p}(w) = w.
\]



\subsection{Homotopy Colimit}

The homotopy colimit:


\[
  \operatorname{hocolim}(\varphi)
\]


captures the global shape of the universe space generated by the kernel.

\subsection{Homology of Universe Space}

Define:


\[
  H_{n}(\varphi) = H_{n}(\operatorname{hocolim}(\varphi)).
\]


These homology groups classify large-scale structural features of the
universe space.

