\section{Denotational Semantics}

The denotational semantics of the Dualatalis language interpret programs
as mathematical structures. Every syntactic construct corresponds to an
object or morphism in a category, topos, homotopy class, or spectral
space.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Semantic Domains}

We define the following semantic domains:

\begin{itemize}
  \item $\mathbf{Mon}$: category of monoids.
  \item $\mathbf{Rew}$: category of rewrite systems.
  \item $\mathbf{VFold}$: category of vanfolds.
  \item $\mathbf{Topos}$: rewriting topos.
  \item $\mathbf{Ho}$: homotopy category of rewrite graphs.
  \item $\mathbf{Spec}$: spectral domain of Koopman operators.
\end{itemize}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Alphabet Semantics}

An alphabet declaration:


\[
  \texttt{alphabet \{A, B, C\}}
\]


denotes the object:


\[
  \Sigma \in \mathbf{Set}.
\]



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Word Semantics}

A word literal:


\[
  w = s_1 s_2 \dots s_n
\]


denotes an element of the free monoid:


\[
  w \in \Sigma^{*} \in \mathbf{Mon}.
\]



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Rule Semantics}

A rule:


\[
  r : \Sigma \to \Sigma^{*}
\]


denotes a monoid endomorphism:


\[
  r : \Sigma^{*} \to \Sigma^{*} \in \mathbf{Mon}.
\]



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Phi Semantics}

The evolution operator:


\[
  \varphi = r_{\mathrm{r}} \circ r_{\mathrm{g}}
\]


denotes an endomorphism in the category of vanfolds:


\[
  \varphi : (\Sigma, w) \to (\Sigma, \varphi(w)) \in \mathbf{VFold}.
\]



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Universe Semantics}

A universe block:


\[
  U = (\Sigma, w_0, \varphi)
\]


denotes an object in the category of vanfolds:


\[
  U \in \mathbf{VFold}.
\]



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Functorial Semantics}

The evolution operator induces a functor:


\[
  F_{\varphi} : \mathbf{VFold}_{\Sigma} \to \mathbf{VFold}_{\Sigma}
\]


defined by:


\[
  F_{\varphi}(\Sigma, w) = (\Sigma, \varphi(w)).
\]



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Topos Semantics}

A rewrite system $(\Sigma, R)$ is interpreted as an object in the
rewriting topos:


\[
  (\Sigma, R) \in \mathbf{Topos}.
\]



Predicates correspond to subobjects:


\[
  P \subseteq \Sigma^{*}.
\]



Logical operations are interpreted as:


\[
  \wedge, \quad \Rightarrow, \quad \forall, \quad \exists
\]


in the internal logic of the topos.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Homotopy Semantics}

The rewrite graph:


\[
  G_{\varphi} = (V, E)
\]


is interpreted as an object in the homotopy category:


\[
  G_{\varphi} \in \mathbf{Ho}.
\]



Universe histories correspond to paths:


\[
  w_0 \to w_1 \to \dots \to w_n.
\]



Homotopy classes correspond to:


\[
  \Pi_{1}(G_{\varphi}).
\]



The global shape of the universe space is:


\[
  \operatorname{hocolim}(\varphi).
\]



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Spectral Semantics}

The Koopman operator:


\[
  U_{\varphi} : \mathcal{F} \to \mathcal{F}
\]


is interpreted in the spectral domain:


\[
  U_{\varphi} \in \mathbf{Spec}.
\]



Eigenfunctions satisfy:


\[
  U_{\varphi} f = \lambda f.
\]



The spectral radius:


\[
  \rho(U_{\varphi})
\]


classifies dynamical regimes.

